ce:section.ce:para:
Transmission electron microscopy (TEM) images were captured using a Hitachi H-8100 electron microscope (Hitachi, Tokyo, Japan) using a voltage of 200 kV. Atomic force microscopy (AFM) experiments were carried out using a Bruker Dimension Icon system. X-ray photoelectron spectra (XPS) were obtained using a PHI Quantera II system (Ulvac-PHI, INC, Japan). Fourier transform infrared (FT-IR) spectra were recorded using a Bruker Vertex 70 infrared spectrometer (resolution 0.4 cm−1). 1H nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectra were acquired at 600 MHz using a Bruker DRX500 spectrometer and the observed chemical shifts expressed relative to tetramethylsilane (TMS) as internal standard. Fluorescent emission and excitation spectra were recorded in aqueous solution using a PerkinElmer LS55 luminescence spectrometer (PerkinElmer Instruments, U.K.) at room temperature (25 °C). Quantum yields (Φ

                           f
                        ) were measured according to established procedures [33,34]. Ultraviolet–visible (UV–vis) absorption spectra were obtained using a UV5800 spectrophotometer. Rhodamine 6G solution (quantum yield 0.98 in EtOH) was chosen as a standard. Absolute values were calculated using a standard reference sample with fixed and known fluorescence quantum yield. In order to minimize re-absorption effects, the absorbencies in the 10 mm fluorescence cuvettes were kept below 0.1 at the excitation wavelength. The concentration of Gd3+ was determined by inductively coupled plasma optical emission spectrometer (ICP-OES, Agilent ICPOES730). The detailed procedures and results can be seen from Experimental Section 1.1 and Fig. S8–S10 in Supporting Information. The GQDs were initially weighted and dissolved via volumetric flask to determine the concentration in our experiments. Meanwhile, the concentrations of GQDs were verified by standard curve method via fluorescence intensity calibration, as shown in Fig. S11–S13. (See Experimental Section 1.2 in Supporting Information).
